ource. Looking at the overall structure, I notice the source document has 12 separate h2-level sections covering different aspects like component configuration, import, config files, properties, lists, and various element types, but the knowledge file consolidates all of this into a single section. This is a substantial reference document with a lot of content.\n\nChecking against the V3 rules for section structure, the rule about reporting issues only applies if there are h2 sections with 2000+ characters AND h3 sections exist but aren't split in the knowledge file. Since the source has h2 sections but no h3 sections, that particular rule doesn't trigger. The section ID format also follows the expected sequential pattern, so there's no issue to report there either. I'm realizing the heading hierarchy in RST is determined by the order of first appearance—the `----` underline marks the document title as h1, while the `====` underlines mark the element sections as h2. So there are actually 12 h2-level sections in the source document, but the knowledge file only has 1 section, which is a significant discrepancy worth flagging according to the V3 rule. I think the V3 rule is using `------` as a generic placeholder for any RST heading marker that represents h2 in context, so the `====` sections here are actually h2-level. The knowledge file has just one section while the source has 12 h2 elements, but since the split condition requires h2 sections with 2000+ characters AND h3 sections to exist, and there are no h3 sections here, the split rule doesn't apply. I'm realizing the V3 rule is really just asking me to count and compare the heading levels between source and knowledge to check if they align.\n\nThe s1 section is definitely over 2000 characters, but again, the split rule only triggers if h3 sections exist, which they don't. The section ID format looks fine with just s1. Now I'm moving into V4 to check the hints completeness, looking at what hints are actually provided.\n\nI notice several attribute names and values are missing from the hints list—things like \"None\" as an autowireType option, plus various attribute names like \"file\", \"dir\", \"encoding\", \"name\", \"class\", and entry-related attributes like \"key\", \"key-name\", and \"value-name\". The V4 check appears to be evaluating whether these gaps are significant. I'm seeing that several attribute names are missing from the hints—specifically `file`, `encoding`, `class`, `ref`, `key`, `key-name`, and `value-name`—which are all documented as property names in the source tables. The most critical gaps are `file` for import and config-file elements, `encoding` for config-file, and `class` as a key configuration attribute. I'm identifying the missing attribute names that should be included in the hints section—`file`, `dir`, `encoding`, `class`, `ref`, `key`, `key-name`, and `value-name`—which represents a minor issue worth flagging since these are documented in the element tables but absent from the hints.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":21876,"cache_read_input_tokens":29807,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":21876,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bd68ba58-02d9-4738-88cc-53e19f72790f","uuid":"8ad835e9-3e5d-4086-a0fe-f84d767afe43"}
